"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690441","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>Information on the risk of re-offending for all women convicted of domestic violence related offences is not available as there is no single offence of domestic violence</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-27T16:11:30.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690441/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690441/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690441/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-17","Domestic Abuse: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what proportion of women convicted of domestic violence-related offences are assessed as being at (a) low, (b) medium and (c) high risk of reoffending.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64141"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690442","Attorney General","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) uses a monitoring flag to collect data to show the number of defendants prosecuted for offences relating to ‘so-called’ honour-based violence (HBV). The flag is applied where any offence of threatening behaviour, violence or abuse has been carried out in the context of HBV. During the financial year 2015-16 the CPS received 216 HBV referrals from the police, 182 of these were prosecuted.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-02-27T14:17:32.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690442/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690442/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690442/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-02-17","Honour Based Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, how many cases dealt with by the CPS were flagged as being cases of honour-based violence in the most recent year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","Wealden","Nusrat Ghani","64191"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690443","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>(a) Data on convictions are the responsibility of the Ministry of Justice. They have informed us they do not hold information on the location of offences at parliamentary constituency level that led to convictions at court centrally.</p><p> </p><p>(b) The Home Office does not hold the requested information on arrests centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collect and publish data on the number of arrests for drug offences broken down by police force area only, and cannot separately identify those arrests that took place in the South Thanet constituency.</p><p> </p><p>The number of arrests for drug offences, by police force area, can be found in the statistical publication ‘Police Powers and Procedures’: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-23T12:48:06.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690443/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690443/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690443/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Drugs: South Thanet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many drug-related (a) convictions and (b) arrests have been made in South Thanet constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","63998"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690444","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Home Office does not hold the requested information centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office collect and publish data on the number and quantity of drugs seized by police force area. Information on the value of each seizure is not collected centrally.</p><p> </p><p>The number and quantity of drugs seized, broken down by police force area, can be found in the statistical publication ‘Drug seizures in England and Wales’: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/seizures-of-drugs-in-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/seizures-of-drugs-in-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2016</a></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-02-23T12:47:06.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690444/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690444/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690444/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Drugs: South Thanet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the value was of drugs seized in South Thanet constituency in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","63999"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690445","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-04-18","<p>An independent judiciary is the cornerstone of the rule of law and is a subject on which my department engages with international partners regularly.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald","64611","2017-04-18T15:18:15.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690445/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690445/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690445/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-17","Judiciary: Political Impartiality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether she has discussed the importance of an independent judiciary with her US counterpart.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690446","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>Operation Pallial is an independent investigation by theNational Crime Agency. The policing costs of the investigation were £3.7 million covering the financial years 2012/13 until 2015/16. The estimated costs for 2016/17 are £730,000. The Home Office does not hold information on the costs in respect of individual strands of this operation or the costs relating to the Crown Prosecution Service or the courts.</p><p>Under Operation Pallial one woman has been arrested, charged and prosecuted. A total of 47 former care staff have been interviewed under caution, either post arrest, or as a consequence of Voluntary Attendance in relation to child abuse or child cruelty.</p><p>On average the length of time between arrest and charge has been 11 months, with a further 11 months between charge and trial at Crown Court.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64055 ; 64056 ; 64057 ; 64305","2017-02-23T12:45:08.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690446/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690446/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690446/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Offences against Children: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many women have been (a) arrested, (b) charged and (c) prosecuted under Operation Pallial.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","64059"
