"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690449","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>Operation Pallial is an independent investigation by theNational Crime Agency. The policing costs of the investigation were £3.7 million covering the financial years 2012/13 until 2015/16. The estimated costs for 2016/17 are £730,000. The Home Office does not hold information on the costs in respect of individual strands of this operation or the costs relating to the Crown Prosecution Service or the courts.</p><p>Under Operation Pallial one woman has been arrested, charged and prosecuted. A total of 47 former care staff have been interviewed under caution, either post arrest, or as a consequence of Voluntary Attendance in relation to child abuse or child cruelty.</p><p>On average the length of time between arrest and charge has been 11 months, with a further 11 months between charge and trial at Crown Court.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","64055 ; 64056 ; 64059 ; 64305","2017-02-23T12:45:08.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690449/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690449/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690449/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Offences against Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the cost of Operation Pallial has been to the public purse; and what the proportion of such costs are (a) police costs, (b) CPS costs and (c) court costs.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","64057"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690450","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not oversee judicial training; the Lord Chief Justice does through the Judicial College.</p><p> </p><p>The issue of religion arises as a factor in a range of cases heard across many jurisdictions. Judges make reasoned and independent decisions based on the evidence presented. If religion is an issue in deciding a case, the parties have the opportunity to present evidence about that to the judge.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-27T15:52:02.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690450/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690450/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690450/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-17","Judges: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the Government has plans to train judges to specialise in the protected characteristic of religion or belief.","false","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","64024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690451","Leader of the House","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Office of the Leader of the House of Commons is an integral part of the Cabinet Office.<br><br>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given to him by my right hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office on 24 February 2017, to Question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-02-17/64159" target="_blank">64159</a>.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2017-02-27T17:35:07.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690451/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690451/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690451/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2017-02-17","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Office who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64173"
