ound, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690453","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Prime Minister’s Office is an integral part of Cabinet Office and is included in this reply.</p><p>The Office for National Statistics publish much of this information each year by Civil Service organization as part of their annual release of Civil Service statistics. The latest data set from 2016 can be found on the ONS website, available at: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p>Departmental breakdowns of the ethnicity and disability pay gaps are not published through the ONS and are not publicly available.</p><p>The Civil Service is committed to being a place where everyone can thrive, regardless of background- with the aim of becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK</p><p>Whilst it is encouraging to see a positive trajectory in terms of diversity representation in the Civil Service, we recognise that there is more to do. That is why in March 2016 the Government published its refreshed Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service, identifying actions to support our staff, increase diverstity in the Civil Service and deliver the best possible public services.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","64159","2017-02-24T11:56:30.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690453/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690453/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690453/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-17","Prime Minister: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in 10 Downing Street who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64175"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690454","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-27","<p>Details of Ministerial UK official visits and official meetings with external organisations and individuals are published quarterly and made available on the gov.uk website.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-27T16:00:09.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690454/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690454/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690454/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-02-17","Food Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has visited any food banks since becoming Prime Minister; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","64053"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690455","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-22","<p>The UK government is working closely with the Commonwealth Secretariat to prepare for the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting 2018. I, along with Cabinet colleagues, will oversee preparations to ensure the Summit is a cross-government effort, supported by a dedicated unit in the Cabinet Office, in line with previous summits.</p><p> </p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-22T14:00:30.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690455/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690455/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690455/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-02-17","Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she has established a temporary or permanent cabinet committee or sub-committee to prepare for the next Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","64084"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690456","Prime Minister","false","2017-02-27","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 31 January 2017, UIN 61889.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-02-27T15:59:30.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690456/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690456/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690456/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-02-17","Judiciary: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, whether she discussed the importance of the independence of the judiciary with the US President on her recent visit to that country.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","64018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690457","Scotland Office","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Scotland Office does not employ staff directly. It is not possible to provide specific pay analysis broken down by representative groups. Many of the representative groups compromise fewer than 5 people, and individuals may become potentially identifiable.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics annually publish the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation, including the Scotland Office, as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2017-02-22T11:56:31.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690457/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690457/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690457/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2017-02-17","Scotland Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64176"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690458","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2017-02-21","<p>The Electoral Commission continually monitors technological developments in order to provide the best possible service to voters. When the Commission started to explore the possibility of providing polling station locations on its website, Democracy Club had already done a lot of work in this area and had already amassed significant expertise on how best to collate and provide this data. The Commission took the view that it would represent better value for money for the taxpayer to work with and further support Democracy Club rather than restart the work they had already commenced.</p><p>Items that are discussed at the Commission Board are formally minuted and these are placed on the Commission’s website. The decision to work with Democracy Club was not made at Board level, but by a member of the Commission’s executive team as a matter of ongoing business. The decision was not minuted.</p><p>The Commission continues to work with Democracy Club ahead of the polls in May 2017. It is taking an active role in encouraging local authorities to provide their data to Democracy Club so that as many voters as possible can benefit from the service.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2017-02-21T17:55:35.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690458/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690458/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690458/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2017-02-17","Polling Stations: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, with reference to the Electoral Commission's Electoral Administration Bulletin Issue 173, published in December 2016, for what reasons the Commission does not provide an online polling station finder service directly; and if the Commission will publish the minutes of meetings held which resulted in the decision not to collate that information internally.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64335"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690459","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2017-02-21","<p>The Electoral Commission has had no discussions with the Minister on the issue of providing online polling station information to political parties. The Commission has briefed the Minister for the Constitution about its partnership with Democracy Club; the Minister is supportive of the initiative, as noted in his recent speech to the conference of the Association of Electoral Administrators on 6 February 2017.</p>","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson",,"2017-02-21T17:56:15.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690459/answer","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690459/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690459/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2017-02-17","Polling Stations: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Houghton and Sunderland South, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, with reference to the Electoral Commission's Electoral Administration Bulletin Issue 173, published in December 2016, what discussions the Commission has had with the Minister for the Cabinet Office on providing Democracy Club's online polling station information to political parties in a usable format.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","64336"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690460","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>Mark Thurston brings a huge array of varied experience across 30 years in the infrastructure sector around Europe, and in UK rail especially. This includes starting out as an apprentice at Transport for London, to major international engineering and infrastructure companies The Nichols Group and CH2M. Whilst at CH2M, he was lead for the Programme Partner joint venture on the Olympics and Crossrail as well as overseeing all of CH2M’s European operations. He has held roles at Metronet, Railtrack, Brown and Root Engineering and Construction.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-27T10:23:31.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690460/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690460/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690460/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish a list of all the rail industry roles and responsibilities previously held by the new Chief Executive Officer of HS2 Ltd.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","64331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690461","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>The new CEO Mark Thurston has left CH2M and will not be working on, Crossrail, the Olympic Delivery Authority or any other projects on behalf of CH2M. He will solely be working for HS2 Ltd.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T10:57:58.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690461/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690461/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690461/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what work will be undertaken by the new chief executive of HS2 Ltd on Crossrail and the Olympic Delivery Authority at CH2M; and what his (a) role, (b) job specification and (c) job title is for those two projects.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","64299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690462","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>a).<strong> Phase Two B Development Partner </strong></p><ul><li>£130m to £170m (based on 2015 prices.)</li></ul><p><strong> </strong></p><p>b). The values those contracts might amount to</p><p> </p><p><strong>Area 1 – Manchester M2 and M3</strong> Lot 1 Mott MacDonald Limited (Lead) / WSP UK LIMITED) - <strong> </strong>£80m- £100m</p><p> </p><p><strong>Area 2 – Leeds L1 and L2 </strong>Lot 2 AECOM Limited (Lead)/ Capita Property Infrastructure Limited / Ingenieria y Economia del Transporte, SA (INECO) - £80m- £100m</p><p> </p><p><strong>Area 3 and EOC - Leeds L3 and L4 </strong>Lot 3 Ove Arup &amp; Partners International Limited -£120m -£150m</p><p> </p><p>(All values are an estimate of the nominal value of each Lot based on 2015 prices)</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T11:21:14.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690462/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690462/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690462/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much will be contracted to be paid from the public purse for (a) the CH2M for the Phase 2b Development Partner contract and (b) each of the Phase 2b Civil Design and Environmental Services for the (i) Lot 1 Mott Macdonald/WSP joint venture, (b) Lot 2 AECOM/Capita/INECO joint venture and (c) Lot 3 Arup.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","64301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690463","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>The construction period for Phase 2b of HS2 is 9 years, from 2024 to 2033. No detailed work has been done to look into the construction planning for stations that would be served by HS2 trains. During design of the scheme over next two years, and before the hybrid Bill is deposited, HS2 Ltd will make an estimate of the construction timescales for various elements of the programme.</p><p> </p><p>We do not provide cost breakdowns for specific items of the HS2 programme due to commercial sensitivities.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-27T11:33:42.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690463/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690463/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690463/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Railway Stations: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will publish his Department's analysis of the (a) cost and (b) duration of construction of the Sheffield Meadowhall High Speed Rail station.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","64315"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690464","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Civil Service is committed to being a place where everyone can thrive, regardless of background- with the aim of becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK</p><p> </p><p>Whilst it is encouraging to see a positive trajectory in terms of diversity representation in the Civil Service, we recognise that there is more to do. That is why in March 2016 the Government published its refreshed Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service, identifying actions to support our staff, increase diverstity in the Civil Service and deliver the best possible public services.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-27T13:35:25.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690464/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690464/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690464/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Department for Transport: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64177"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690465","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) has not made any assessment of Exeter City Council’s proposal to make Exeter congestion free by 2025.</p><p> </p><p>The DfT is committed to an integrated transport policy which addresses the important issues of traffic congestion and environmental pollution. Transport matters, it brings real change to people’s lives and that is why it is at the heart of the Government’s infrastructure agenda.</p><p> </p><p>The Chancellor’s Autumn Statement showed this commitment by giving new funding for the local roads network, specifically £1.1bn over 4 years to relieve congestion to increase the quality, performance and safety of the roads we use every day.</p><p> </p><p>The Government recognises the role that new technology can play. On 21 February 2017, the Department announced that nineteen councils across England will receive £50,000 to £300,000 each for their ideas to improve journeys through digital innovation. These projects will feature cutting edge technology such as apps and sensors which can be used to cut congestion, improve parking in city centres and alert drivers when electric car charging points become available.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-24T11:28:23.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690465/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690465/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690465/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Road Traffic: Exeter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he has made an assessment of Exeter City Council's strategy to make Exeter congestion free by 2025; and what measures the Government is taking to reduce traffic in urban areas.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","64198"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690466","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>There are no plans for any further public consultation before the smart motorway opens between junctions 32 to 35a of the M1.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-22T17:38:02.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690466/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690466/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690466/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","M1: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2017 to Question 62124, whether there will be further public consultation on measures to mitigate increases in air pollution before the smart motorway, between junctions 32 to 35a of the M1 opens.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64245"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690467","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Chancellor’s Spending Review announcement in November 2015 set out an updated funding envelope of £55.7bn in 2015 prices for delivering the HS2 project. The envelope was previously £50.1bn in 2011 prices as set out in the 2013 Spending Round. The cost of building HS2 has not changed since the 2013 Spending Round, as the long-term funding envelope has simply been uprated to 2015 prices to take account of inflation. Cost estimates for specific sections of route were revised in accordance with these figures. We do not provide further funding breakdowns for specific items due to commercial sensitivities.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T10:51:02.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690467/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690467/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690467/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2017 to Question 62120, on High Speed Railway Line 2: South Yorkshire, what the increase has been in the estimated cost of the Meadowhall route since the first estimate was made; and for what reasons that estimated cost has risen.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64247"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690468","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>In developing proposals for HS2 before the 2013 consultation, HS2 Ltd published a large number of alternative routes in South Yorkshire (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/options-for-phase-two-of-the-high-speed-rail-network" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/options-for-phase-two-of-the-high-speed-rail-network</a>).</p><p> </p><p>Subsequently, HS2 Ltd has reviewed these and some other alternatives in preparing recommendations to the Secretary of State before the November 2016 Command Paper. The ‘M18’ route and the spur to Sheffield are two of these alternatives. To prevent unnecessary blight, details of other alternatives have not been published.</p><p> </p><p>As HS2 Ltd develops the programme, including in response to the current consultation, it will continue to look at route refinements to meet engineering, environmental, stakeholder and other factors.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T10:45:39.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690468/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690468/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690468/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 1 February 2017 to Question 62138, on High Speed Railway Line 2: South Yorkshire, what the alternative routes to Meadowhall are that HS2 Ltd has carried out work into (a) in the past, (b) more recently and (c) currently.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","64248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690469","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>As of February 2017, 202 staff of HS2 Ltd are paid £75,000 and above.</p><p> </p><p>It would be inappropriate to provide a list of job titles and the salary for each individual employee as this would make personal information available.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T11:25:24.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690469/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690469/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690469/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which employees of HS2 Ltd as of 13 February 2017 are paid £75,000 or more per year; and what the job titles and salaries of such employees are.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","64214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690470","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>a) The delay repay compensation figures for all Train Operating Companies covering the years 2009-10 to 2014-15 are published on the GOV.UK website at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/train-operating-companies-passenger-charter-compensation-between-2009-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/train-operating-companies-passenger-charter-compensation-between-2009-to-2015</a>. Figures for the 2015-16 financial year for all Train Operating Companies are expected to be published on the GOV.UK website later this year. Releasing all the figures at the same time will allow everyone to see them together which will provide a clear and consistent publication and help avoid misinterpretation and confusion.</p><p> </p><p>b) Under their track access agreement, compensation for unplanned disruption passes between Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) and Network Rail based upon which party is responsible for each disruptive incident. The Department does not see the breakdown of the compensation paid by each party. The net figures covering the years 2011-12 to 2014-15, are published on Network Rail's website (‘Payments for disruption on the railway made under schedule 8’) at the following address:</p><p><a href="http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/#_blank" target="_blank">http://www.networkrail.co.uk/transparency/datasets/</a></p><p> </p><p>Payments to train operators, made through the performance regime, are not designed to cover the refund claims which passengers make. They are instead designed to hold train operators financially neutral to the long-term revenue impact as a result of disruption.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-27T14:02:40.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690470/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690470/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Southern: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much Southern Railway has (a) paid to passengers in compensation and (b) received in compensation from Network Rail since the start of that franchise.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","64137"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690471","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-22","<p>In 2011, the Government consulted on the proposed strategy for a national high speed rail network. A decision to proceed with High Speed 2 was taken in January 2012 (Cm 8247). The total spend on High Speed 2 from the financial year 2009/10 to 2011/12 was £87.7 million.</p><p>Expenditure on HS2 from 2012/13 onwards is included in the long-term funding envelope for delivering HS2. The funding envelope was restated in 2015 prices in Spending Review 2015 at £55.7 billion, including rolling stock. The funding envelope is net of any proceeds from selling Land &amp; Property that is not directly needed for construction of the railway.</p><p>I am committed to managing both the cost of HS2 and ensuring maximum value for the taxpayer, and delivering within the funding available.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-22T10:42:17.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690471/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690471/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what is the latest estimated total cost of High Speed 2, including rolling stock, from 2009 to the date on which the first trains run on all phases of the lines.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","64093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690472","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR) were compliant with their performance benchmarks until March 2015, when they triggered a Remedial Plan Notice from the Department, culminating in an agreed Remedial Plan. GTR remained compliant with the Remedial Plan benchmarks until industrial relations issues, which commenced in April 2016, caused significant disruption to services meaning performance benchmarks have been exceeded.</p><p> </p><p>However, GTR are entitled to claim Force Majeure against this disruption as per the terms of their Franchise Agreement, which they have done, and this may lead to changes in their position against each benchmark. We are currently discussing the Force Majeure claim with GTR before making our final determination.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-27T13:54:19.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690472/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690472/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Govia Thameslink Railway: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, in which reporting periods GTR's performance has met the specified benchmarks set out in the franchise agreement since that agreement was signed.","false","Biography information for Helen Hayes","Dulwich and West Norwood","Helen Hayes","64136"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690473","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) is unable to identify the number of reminders issued specifically to keepers of vehicles that attract a nil rate of vehicle excise duty and how many of those keepers re-licensed or declared a Statutory Off Road Notification (SORN) as a result.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-24T11:47:21.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690473/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690473/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many demands for £0.00 have been issued by the Driver and Vehicle and Licensing Agency for vehicle tax; and how many of those demands were deemed to have been paid in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64140"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690474","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-24","<p>There are currently around 37 million licensed vehicles recorded on the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) database with a further three million vehicles subject to a Statutory Off Road Notification (SORN).</p><p> </p><p>In 2016 the DVLA issued 15,656 late licensing penalties to keepers of vehicles that attract a nil rate of vehicle excise duty who did not renew their vehicle licence.</p><p> </p><p>There are a number of reasons why a vehicle may attract a nil rate of vehicle excise duty. These include vehicles where the registered keeper is in receipt of, or is acting on behalf of an individual in receipt of Disability Living Allowance or Personal Independence Payment or where vehicles are in a Historic, Crown or Emergency tax class.</p><p> </p><p>All vehicle licences must be renewed on an annual or six-monthly basis whether vehicle excise duty is payable or not. This helps to ensure that the keeper information held on the DVLA’s record is accurate and that the details relating to the nil rate of vehicle excise duty remain correct. For example, a nil rate of vehicle excise duty may no longer be applicable if the registered keeper changes or the current keeper’s circumstances change.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-24T11:32:32.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690474/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690474/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many penalty notices the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency has issued in respect of vehicle tax where the tax due was £0.00 in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64138"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690475","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold investment data in the format requested and this could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. However, over the last five years, the Government has made significant investment which benefit East Kent. This includes the introduction of several new high speed services (including at Martin Mill station); ongoing work to deliver line speed improvements between Ashford International and Ramsgate and a traction power supply upgrade to facilitate the operation of longer trains. The train operator has committed to making improvements worth more than £70m across the franchise area by 2018.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-02-27T17:06:34.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690475/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690475/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Railways: Kent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has spent on rail improvements in East Kent in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","64002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690476","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>HS2 Ltd’s search consultants, Heidrick and Struggles, conducted a worldwide search and an advertisement was placed in the Sunday Times. Candidates were interviewed initially by Heidrick and Struggles and a shortlist was developed. The final interview was conducted by a panel of 7, which included the Chair of HS2 Ltd, the Department for Transport (DfT) Permanent Secretary, the Director General for High Speed 2, a senior Treasury Official and non-Executive Directors of HS2 Ltd and DfT. References were taken and the appointment was approved by the Secretary of State for Transport.</p><p> </p><p>Mark Thurston brings a huge array of varied experience across 30 years in the infrastructure sector around Europe, and in UK rail especially. This includes starting out as an apprentice at Transport for London, to major international engineering and infrastructure companies The Nichols Group and CH2M. At CH2M, he was the lead for the Programme Partner joint venture on the Olympics and Crossrail as well as overseeing all of CH2M’s European operations.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-27T10:41:42.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690476/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690476/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what due diligence processes his Department and HS2 Ltd carried out on the suitability of the new Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of HS2 Ltd; and what that CEO's experience is of leading a major UK infrastructure project.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","64112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690477","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-27","<p>HS2 Ltd conducted an extensive global search for the right candidate to take forward one of the largest and most exciting infrastructure programmes in the world. The process was led by Sir David Higgins, supported by Heidrick and Struggles (an international executive search firm) that identified 20 candidates from four continents (including America, Australia, Asia, as well as Europe).</p><p> </p><p>The job specification which set out the skills and experience criteria were published on the HS2 Ltd website.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Skills</strong></p><p> </p><p>► Information analysis - An ability to assimilate complex, ambiguous and often incomplete information, in order to take action providing clear direction and purpose to the organisation and its stakeholders.</p><p>► An ability to understand and focus on detail as needed whilst maintaining the strategic vision and overview to keep the project focused.</p><p>► Public speaking &amp; Ambassadorial skills - to lead innovation within the broader industry, working with technical bodies, trade associations, the supply chain and government.</p><p>► Ability to build, lead and motivate top executive teams and consensus within these teams and the board.</p><p><strong>Knowledge</strong></p><p> </p><p>► An ability to assimilate complex, ambiguous and often incomplete information, in order to take action providing clear direction and purpose to the organisation and its stakeholders.</p><p>► Knowledge of best practice approaches to embedding continuous improvement culture as the organisation shifts from concept to delivery and adapts accordingly.</p><p>► Knowledge of inclusive leadership techniques and approaches.</p><p>► <em>Qualifications</em><strong>: </strong>Applicants will most likely have a strong academic or professional training and have experience of dealing with complex engineering and business issues.</p><p><strong>Experience</strong></p><p> </p><p>► Experience of leading a successful transformation of a large complex commercially-focused delivery organisation, achieving significant improvements in efficiency, effectiveness and customer service.</p><p>► Experience of leading an ingrained Health and Safety culture through personal leadership and commitment.</p><p>► Experience of effective strategic risk management, change control processes and capital allocation on large scale capital intensive projects or within organisations delivering in this environment.</p><p>► Experience of dealing with the procurement of a complex supply chain.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-27T11:25:10.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690477/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690477/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690477/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","High Speed Two: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria his Department set out in recruiting the new Chief Executive Officer of HS2 Ltd on a record of successful delivery.","false","Biography information for Robert Flello","Stoke-on-Trent South","Robert Flello","64113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690478","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Government is currently consulting on a draft Airports National Policy Statement, with the consultation closing on 25 May 2017. Following consultation and Parliamentary scrutiny, the Government will consider all the responses received and, if it chooses to proceed, could then lay a proposed final Airports National Policy Statement before Parliament. It would be inappropriate for the Government to speculate on the content of any final Airports National Policy Statement before all of the relevant procedural steps have been taken. I would encourage the Hon Member to set out his views on the issue of landfill clearing costs in his response to the consultation.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-24T10:35:55.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690478/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690478/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-02-17","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the final National Policy Statement on Aviation will include an estimate of the cost of clearing landfill necessary for a third runway at Heathrow; and whether that cost will be borne by the public purse.","false","Biography information for Adam Afriyie","Windsor","Adam Afriyie","64105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690479","Wales Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Wales Office does not employ staff directly. It is not possible to provide specific pay analysis broken down by representative groups. Some of the representative groups compromise fewer than 5 people, and individuals may become potentially identifiable.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics annually publish the highest and median salary for each Civil Service organisation, including the Wales Office, as part of the Civil Service Statistics. This information can be found on the Office for National Statistics website:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/datasets/medianpayannexb</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2017-02-27T16:28:09.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690479/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690479/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2017-02-17","Wales Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64179"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690480","Women and Equalities","false","2017-02-27","<p>The most recent publication of<em> Civil Service Statistics </em>was released by the Office for National Statistics in October 2016, using data gathered from departments as of 31<sup>st</sup> March 2016. The latest set of data can be found on the ONS website via this weblink:</p><p><a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p> </p><p>The Civil Service is committed to being a place where everyone can thrive, regardless of background - with the aim of becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Whilst it is encouraging to see a positive trajectory in terms of diversity representation in the Civil Service, we recognise that there is more to do. That is why in March 2016 the Government published its refreshed Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service, identifying actions to support our staff, increase diversity in the Civil Service and deliver the best possible public services.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-02-27T17:39:40.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690480/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690480/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-02-17","Government Equalities Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in the Government Equalities Office who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64167"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690481","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Civil Service is committed to being a place where everyone can thrive, regardless of background- with the aim of becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK</p><p> </p><p>Whilst it is encouraging to see a positive trajectory in terms of diversity representation in the Civil Service, we recognise that there is more to do. That is why in March 2016 the Government published its refreshed Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service, identifying actions to support our staff, increase diversity in the Civil Service and deliver the best possible public services.</p><p> </p><p>The Office for National Statistics provide information on pay for the whole of the Civil Service, using data gathered from departments as of 31st March 2016. The latest set of data can be found here: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a></p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-27T17:56:34.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690481/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690481/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64180"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690482","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>At present we do not hold any data relating to fit notes so are unable to provide the information requested. We are working with NHS Digital towards making anonymised fit note statistics available. These statistics will include information on the main diagnosed condition (ICD-10) and the location of the Clinical Commissioning Group which will allow the number of fit notes issued for both England and Leeds to be identified.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-27T12:37:24.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690482/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690482/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Sick Leave: Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many fit notes were issued to people as a result of musculoskeletal conditions in (a) England and (b) Leeds in (i) 2015 and (ii) 2016.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","64195"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690483","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>On 12 December 2016, I set out the scope of the 2017 review of automatic enrolment. On 8 February 2017 I set out further detail on the review, including its terms of reference and the membership of the external advisory group. We will publish a report to Parliament towards the end of 2017.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-02-23T16:35:40.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690483/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690483/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Occupational Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will set out a timetable for the automatic enrolment review.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","64197"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690484","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Government is spending record amounts on supporting carers, including those in Scotland, through the benefit system. Carer’s Allowance itself provides a measure of financial support and recognition for people who give up the opportunity of full-time employment in order to provide regular and substantial care for a severely disabled person.</p><p> </p><p>Means tested benefits such as Income Support and Pension Credit include additional amounts for carers and are available to low income carers of working age and over state pension age respectively. The additional amounts mean that lower-income carers can be better off than others who receive these benefits.</p><p> </p><p>Both Carer’s Allowance, and the additional amounts for carers, are paid in addition to the extra costs disability benefits (such as Attendance Allowance), which are designed to provide a contribution towards the extra costs that people with long-term health conditions and disabilities can face.</p><p> </p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-22T11:50:37.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690484/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690484/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Carers' Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will assess the merits of introducing a care costs payment for all carers, including those over state pension age.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","64222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690485","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The information available for the number of Employment and Support Allowance claimants by disability is published and can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/default.asp</a></p><p> </p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-27T12:32:28.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690485/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690485/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Employment and Support Allowance: Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) England and (b) Leeds are in receipt of employment and support allowance as a result of disability related to a musculoskeletal condition.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","64196"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690486","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>Distances and journey times have been calculated using a number of sources including AA route mapping, Google Maps, local public transport routes and local information provided by DWP colleagues.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-23T16:11:47.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690486/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690486/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's paper entitled Proposal for the future of Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree jobcentres, of January 2017, how the travelling distances between the jobcentre offices that are proposed for closure and the new offices have been measured.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690487","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Department will not breach the mobility rules within employee’s contracts as part of proposals to relocate staff and services from the current Jobcentre at Eastern Avenue, Sheffield. If an employee were to move outside of their contractual mobility it would only be with their agreement. We expect all staff to be relocated to nearby offices. Individual meetings between local DWP managers and their staff began after the announcements on 26 January 2017 and this is an opportunity to discuss mobility or any other aspects of the proposals.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that DWP staff are our most valuable resource and we will continue to ensure that there is proper consultation with them and trade unions.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T12:25:35.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690487/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690487/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Sheffield","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2017 to Question 63189, what steps his Department plans to take for those employees at Eastern Avenue, Sheffield for whom a move would breach the mobility rule but who do not consent to a change.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","64246"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690488","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>Within the context of claimant journeys, we believe that it is a reasonable expectation that a claimant travels an additional distance of up to 3 miles, or 20 minutes by public transport, to the new Jobcentre. This may mean slightly longer and slightly shorter journeys for some individual claimants and we have taken this into account when setting the criteria.</p><p> </p><p>There are large areas of the country where claimants have always travelled further than this. A proportion of claimants may also live closer to the proposed new Jobcentre location, so this will remain a convenient location for those people. We therefore view these criteria to be within reasonable expectations.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-23T16:27:24.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690488/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690488/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's paper entitled Proposal for the future of Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree jobcentres, of January 2017, what the evidential basis is for the statement that it is a reasonable expectation that claimants travel to an office within three miles or 20 minutes by public transport of their existing jobcentre and whether this applies to claimants who have already had to move to visiting one of those two jobcentres as a result.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690489","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>No assessment has been made of the distances between Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree Jobcentres and Huyton Jobcentre. This is because the proposals are to relocate Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree Jobcentres to High Park House. We have not calculated any distances based on claimants travelling in a straight line as it would be unreasonable to expect them to be able to do so.</p><p> </p><p>According to the information from Google Maps and other sources, the Jobcentre at High Park House, is 1.8 miles away and approximately 8 minutes by car from Liverpool Edge Hill Jobcentre; and 2.9 miles away, approximately 14 minutes by car from Liverpool Wavertree Jobcentre.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-23T16:19:45.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690489/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690489/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's paper entitled Proposal for the future of Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree jobcentres, of January 2017, how many miles to the decimal point the jobcentres in (a) Wavertree and (b) Edge Hill are from the Jobcentre in Huyton (i) in a straight line and (ii) by road.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690490","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>Distances and journey times have been calculated using variety of methods to improve accuracy, including Google Maps and AA route mapping, and information collected about local public transport routes with input from local DWP colleagues.</p><p> </p><p>Regardless of the proposed changes, it is important for claimants to allow sufficient time to attend appointments, taking into consideration the time of day and any local traffic conditions, as they do now.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-23T16:20:02.65Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690490/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690490/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's paper entitled Proposal for the future of Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree jobcentres, of January 2017, how the travelling times by public transport between jobcentre offices that are proposed for closure and the new offices have been calculated; and on what (a) time of day and (b) traffic conditions those calculations are based.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690491","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-23","<p>Information on the numbers of claimants that attend on a daily, weekly or monthly basis is not available. The number of claimants for each office is as follows:</p><p> </p><p>The JSA claimant count for Toxteth JCP is 851 and UC is 1389</p><p>The JSA claimant count for Edge Hill JCP is 647 and UC is 1083</p><p>The JSA claimant count for Wavertree JCP is 438 and UC is 742</p><p>The JSA claimant count for Huyton JCP is 882 and UC is 2434</p><p> </p><p>This information refers to January 2017, and is available from the following link: <a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-23T16:08:28.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690491/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690491/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Liverpool","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's paper entitled Proposal for the future of Liverpool Edge Hill and Liverpool Wavertree jobcentres, of January 2017, how many visits are made to the jobcentres in (a) Toxteth, (b) Edge Hill, (c) Wavertree and (d) Huyton each (i) day, (ii) week and (iii) month by claimants who are required to report every two weeks.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","64225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690492","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>A total of 30 Jobcentres are outside of the criteria of 3 miles and 20 minutes by public transport of the existing Jobcentre.</p><p> </p><p>The list of Jobcentres subject to public consultation has been published and documentation is available to view at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date</a>=</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:11:47.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690492/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690492/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of jobcentres due to close under proposals announced on 30 January 2017 which are not within three miles or 20 minutes by public transport of an existing jobcentre.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","64208"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690493","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>Our green paper on social justice will be published in due course. It will set out our approach to tackling child poverty and disadvantage.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T11:57:24.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690493/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690493/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Welfare State: Consultation Papers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to publish the social justice green paper before the 2017 Budget statement.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","64250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690494","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The information requested is not readily available, and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:00:19.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690494/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690494/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Income Support and Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people claimed both income support and any element of tax credits in the most recent year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","64127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690495","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>This information is not available.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-02-27T12:27:29.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690495/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690495/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Sick Leave: Musculoskeletal Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) England and (b) Leeds have been signed off work permanently as a result of disability related to a musculoskeletal condition in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","64134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690496","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>It is estimated that just under a quarter of in-work tax credit claimants receive income from self-employment. This proportion has remained broadly stable since 2012-13.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs continues to monitor trends in self-employment amongst tax credit claimants to inform their expenditure forecasts, policy development and operational performance.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-22T10:49:18.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690496/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690496/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-17","Self-employed: Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of trends in the level of self-employment on distribution of in-work tax credits.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","64095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690497","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>We recognise and encourage volunteering and unpaid work opportunities, such as the Territorial Army or Army Cadets, as an excellent way of preparing for work and improving the claimant's prospects of finding work. Work coaches are encouraged to discuss voluntary and unpaid work opportunities where appropriate with a claimant. However, guidance does not list individual organisations.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T16:20:27.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690497/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690497/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Unemployed People: Territorial Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance is given to Jobcentre Plus staff to encourage jobseekers to join the Territorial Army or Army Cadets.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","64091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690498","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>We have considered the wider impacts of the local economy when developing our proposals for Alexandria Jobcentre. The economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace and staff currently based at Alexandria jobcentre already live in the broader area around the site. While we expect the majority of these staff to be relocated, it is unlikely that a significant proportion of them will also move their place of residence.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:15:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690498/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690498/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment has been made of the effect on the local economy of moving 15 jobs from Alexandria Jobcentre Plus in West Dunbartonshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690499","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>We are not yet in a position to share the expected figure due to commercial confidentiality pending completion of legal processes and staff consultations. We expect to make savings for the tax payer from merging offices by reducing running costs and making best use of both office space available.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T16:50:51.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690499/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690499/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the expected costs are of relocating staff and resources from Alexandria Jobcentre Plus in West Dunbartonshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690500","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-27","<p>Information about the volume and outcomes of appeals to the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) is published on gov.uk and the following table is a further breakdown of that information.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong> </strong> <strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Personal Independence Payment appeals in favour of the appellant in the </strong><strong><sup>1</sup></strong><strong>Greenock venue.</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January – December 2015</p></td><td><p>83</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>January – September 2016 (the latest period for which figures are available)</p></td><td><p>114</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Greenock venue, includes all cases heard at this venue. Appeals are attributed to the hearing venue nearest to the appellants’ home address and for those living in Inverclyde this is the Greenock Venue.</p><p> </p><p>SSCS data are registered to the venue nearest to the appellants’ home address. Data based on the appellants’ actual address cannot be retrieved but reports can be produced detailing the numbers of cases that were dealt with at one of our Regional centres or venues.</p><p> </p><p>Although care is taken when processing and analysing the data, the details are subject to inaccuracies inherent in any large-scale case management system and are the best data that are available.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-27T15:54:16.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690500/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690500/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-02-17","Personal Independence Payment: Inverclyde","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many successful appeals against Personal Independence Payments awards there were in Inverclyde in (a) 2015 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","64129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690501","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","Throughout the development of this project, the department has been mindful of its duties under section 149 of the Equality Act 2010, and in particular the duty to have regard to eliminate discrimination, advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations between those who have a protected characteristic and those who don’t. Statistical analysis has informed high-level decision-making. Site-specific information will be reflected in the final decisions.","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T16:45:33.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690501/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690501/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when an Equality Impact Assessment will be published on the proposal to close the Alexandria Jobcentre in West Dunbartonshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690502","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues in Alexandria Jobcentre. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to comment on the potential for redundancy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T16:55:16.057Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690502/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690502/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690502/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether any compulsory redundancies will result from closure of the Alexandria Jobcentre in West Dunbartonshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690503","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>There will be no public consultation on the proposal to close Alexandria Jobcentre as the proposed move to merge with Dumbarton Jobcentre is 3.4 miles away and 18 minutes by public transport. We have committed to a public consultation for offices over three miles and 20 minutes away by public transport.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:17:38.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690503/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690503/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether a public consultation will take place over the proposal to close the Alexandria Jobcentre in West Dunbartonshire constituency.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690504","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department has sought, where feasible, to merge sites in close proximity as part of its overall review of estate. Merging the staff and services from Alexandria Jobcentre into Dumbarton Jobcentre optimises use of space, ensures value for money and enables effective delivery of services to the public. Alexandria Jobcentre is 46% underutilised, meaning that we are spending money on rent for space that is unused rather than on services and support.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:04:42.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690504/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690504/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what criteria were used to identify the Alexandria Jobcentre Plus in West Dunbartonshire constituency for closure.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690505","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>The information requested is not available. However, such information that is available is in the tables and provides the number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit (required to seek work) claimants; plus the number of claims to Employment and Support Allowance and Income Support from people who are served by (a) Alexandria Jobcentre and (b) in the West Dunbartonshire constituency.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Table (a) Alexandria Jobcentre</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>The number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit claimants attending Alexandria Jobcentre</p></td><td><p>The number of people making a new claim to Employment and Support Allowance and attending Alexandria Jobcentre</p></td><td><p>The number of people making a new claim to Income Support and attending Alexandria Jobcentre</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>December 2016</p></td><td><p>December 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>150</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>42</p></td><td rowspan="2"><p>5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>340</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Table (b) West Dunbartonshire Constituency</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>The number of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Universal Credit claimants in the West Dunbartonshire Constituency</p></td><td><p>The number of Employment and Support Allowance claimants in the West Dunbartonshire Constituency</p></td><td><p>The number of Income Support claimants in the West Dunbartonshire Constituency</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>January 2017</p></td><td><p>August 2016</p></td><td><p>August 2016</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Female</p></td><td><p>615</p></td><td><p>3,000</p></td><td><p>1,210</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Male</p></td><td><p>1,430</p></td><td><p>3,060</p></td><td><p>320</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T17:24:40.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690505/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690505/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: Dumbartonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants are currently served by the Alexandria Jobcentre Plus in West Dunbartonshire constituency; and how many of these are (a) disabled people and (b) women.","false","Biography information for Martin Docherty-Hughes","West Dunbartonshire","Martin Docherty-Hughes","64108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690506","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-27","<p>New Enterprise Allowance is available nationally and has so far supported over 8,600 business startups in Scotland. Support for disadvantaged communities in Scotland is a devolved responsibility.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-27T16:39:02.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690506/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690506/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Small Businesses: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps his Department is taking to promote entrepreneurship in disadvantaged communities in Scotland.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","64068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690507","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The date of the last ministerial visit to a jobcentre specifically in Coventry South could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p><p> </p><p>The last ministerial visit to a jobcentre in the West Midlands was on the 2<sup>nd</sup> February 2017. The Minister for Employment, Damian Hinds MP, visited Solihull.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T16:06:25.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690507/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690507/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date a Minister of his Department last visited a jobcentre in (a) Coventry South and (b) the West Midlands.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","64048"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690508","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>All security passes allowing access to the Department are issued locally and controlled by each office.</p><p> </p><p>Centrally held records are not kept and the information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-22T16:49:19.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690508/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690508/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many security passes to access his Department have been issued to employees of (a) Serco, (b) Capita, (c) Atos, (d) Concentrix and (e) G4S over the last year.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64044"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690509","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>Within the 2012 scheme of child maintenance, a broad spectrum of taxable income can be taken into account in the maintenance calculation as part of a variation.</p><p> </p><p>We believe all parents have a responsibility to financially contribute to their children’s upbringing and the best way we have of establishing a fair contribution is a calculation of their liability based on their income level.</p><p> </p><p>The definition of income within variations is designed to make the best use of additional sources of taxable income captured by self-assessment, referred to as ‘unearned income’. This includes income from property, savings and investments and other miscellaneous sources.</p><p> </p><p>Receiving ‘unearned income’ information directly from HM Revenue and Customs makes it more difficult for individuals to seek to minimise the amount of child maintenance they pay. A variation can also be considered if a receiving parent has evidence that a paying parent is diverting income.</p><p> </p><p>We have no plans to widen our variation categories further.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-02-22T16:42:30.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690509/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690509/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment into the potential merits of amending the Child Maintenance Services' (CMS) variation rules to (a) better reflect the financial capacity of a person to pay and (b) include categories of wealth which fall outside the CMS criteria.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","64052"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690510","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>Waterfront House Annesley is a relatively small processing office and does not fit with our long term strategic aim to have large multi-functional, digitally enabled processing offices. We have more processing capacity across our national network than we need and as a consequence, Waterfront House is no longer needed. The proposal is to rebalance the work to other locations across the national network.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: We will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T15:32:41.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690510/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690510/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690510/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Annesley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, by what criteria his Department's back-of-house administrative site at Annesley has been selected for closure.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","64039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690511","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues in Waterfront House, Annesley. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to confirm where staff currently based at Waterfront House, Annesley will be relocated to until the consultation process is concluded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T12:19:50.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690511/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690511/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Annesley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, where staff based at his Department's back-of-house administrative site at Annesley will be relocated to after its planned closure.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","64040"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690512","Department of Health","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency updated its description of homeopathy on Gov.uk on 27 January. Content on other websites is a matter for other providers.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-22T09:53:27.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690512/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690512/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-17","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 31 January 2017 to Question 61848, if he will take steps to amend the definition of the philosophy of homeopathy (a) on the NHS Choices website and (b) in other public-facing media.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","64041"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690513","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Secretary of State regularly visits DWP sites, including Jobcentres, in different parts of the country.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T15:38:36.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690513/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690513/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690513/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Jobcentres: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to visit a jobcentre in (a) Coventry South and (b) the West Midlands.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","64045"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690515","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>We have considered the wider impacts of the local economy when developing our proposals for the processing site at Annesley. The economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace and the staff currently based at Annesley already live in the broader area around the site. While we expect the majority of these staff to be relocated, it is unlikely that a significant proportion of them will also move their place of residence.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T12:02:32.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690515/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690515/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690515/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Annesley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make an assessment of the relocation of jobs from his Department's Annesley back-of-house site on the local economy.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","64030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690516","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues in Waterfront House, Annesley. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to comment on the potential for redundancy.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T12:07:18.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690516/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690516/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690516/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Annesley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether there will be compulsory redundancies as a result of the planned closure of his Department's Annesley back-of-house site.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","64031"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690517","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions is now consulting with colleagues in Waterfront House, Annesley. We are seeking to relocate, or offer alternative roles, to all employees affected by the proposed closure.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to stress that this is a proposed closure: we will make a final decision informed by the consultation process with our colleagues. We are not therefore in a position to confirm expected costs of relocating staff and resources from Waterfront House, Annesley until the consultation process is concluded.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-02-22T12:12:55.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690517/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690517/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690517/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-02-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Annesley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the expected costs are of relocating staff and resources from his Department's Annesley back-of-house site.","false","Biography information for Gloria De Piero","Ashfield","Gloria De Piero","64032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690518","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Government published the Industrial Strategy Green Paper on 23 January 2017.</p><p> </p><p>This document outlines how Government intends to build on the diverse strengths of our cities and regions, including Exeter, using record investment in infrastructure, research and innovation and inward investment to ensure higher growth is seen across the UK.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome the views of people, businesses and organisations across the country, which is why ministers from this department are undertaking an extensive regional engagement programme and will be visiting the South-West shortly.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-27T17:38:32.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690518/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690518/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690518/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Industry: Exeter","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to ensure that the greater Exeter area contributes to the Government's industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","63991"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690519","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>The UK Government is committed to new nuclear as an important part of the UK’s energy mix, having signed a deal for the first new nuclear power station in a generation. Government continues to work closely with partners as they develop proposals to see Moorside built.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T14:27:31.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690519/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690519/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690519/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Nuclear Power Stations: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions his Department has had with firms to invite interest to invest in the planned nuclear plant at Moorside; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","64027"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690520","Department of Health","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department reviews the impact of tobacco control measures on an ongoing basis, including by statutory requirement, as part of its policy development. The impact of individual measures is also assessed in advance of implementation through impact assessments, which are made publically available.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-27T15:53:17.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690520/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690520/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690520/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-17","Tobacco: Retail Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make an assessment of the cumulative effect of tobacco control measures on small retailers over the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","63995"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690521","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-23","<p>The Office for National Statistics publishes statistics on the number of enterprise “births” in Thanet in its publication <em>Business Demography</em>. A “birth” occurs when a business appears on the Inter-Departmental Business Register, following registration for either VAT or PAYE.</p><p> </p><p>The following table gives “births” in Thanet for the most recent five years available.</p><p> </p><p>2011 400</p><p>2012 390</p><p>2013 535</p><p>2014 525</p><p>2015 545</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2016 is expected to be published later this year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-23T15:24:22.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690521/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690521/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690521/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Small Businesses: South Thanet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many small businesses have opened in South Thanet in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Craig Mackinlay","South Thanet","Craig Mackinlay","64003"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690522","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>The proposed nuclear plant at Moorside could deliver up to 3.8GW of gross electricy capacity. The developers of the project, NuGen, estimate this will provide 7% of the UK’s electricity needs – equivalent to powering 6 million homes.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T14:29:27.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690522/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690522/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690522/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Nuclear Power Stations: Cumbria","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential contribution to domestic energy production of the planned Moorside nuclear plant; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","64005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690523","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Strike Price for Hinkley Point C accounts for all charges incurred by the developer in the production of electricity, including the cost of land, the generator’s share of transmission losses and an expectation of Transmission Use of Service Charges. Balancing services are not accounted for as the Strike Price for Hinkley Point C only includes costs that are directly incurred by the project.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-22T16:56:19.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690523/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690523/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690523/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Hinkley Point C Power Station: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what account was taken of (a) the cost of land, (b) the effect on the transmission system and (c) balancing costs of the strike price for Hinkley Point C.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","64043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690524","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Electricity Generation Costs report focuses on estimates of the levelised costs of electricity generation. These levelised costs cover the total capital and operating costs accruing to the owner/operator of a generation asset.</p><p>To improve the Department’s understanding of the impacts of individual electricity generation technologies, Frontier Economics were commissioned to develop a comprehensive framework to define whole system impacts and their components and drivers, which can be applied to a range of electricity generation technologies. The resulting methodology report and its peer reviews will be published in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-22T11:43:37.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690524/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690524/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690524/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Electricity Generation: Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 11 January 2017 to Question 58726, on wind power, whether the costs associated with electricity generation that make up each Strike Price comparator in the BEIS Electricity Generation Cost report are based on Frontier Economics' research into whole system impacts; and what plans he has to publish that research.","false","Biography information for Callum McCaig","Aberdeen South","Callum McCaig","64050"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690525","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>We have launched a consultation on an Industrial Strategy, which sets out the Government’s approach to building an economy that delivers high wages, high skills, high productivity and creates the conditions for competitive, world leading businesses across the UK. We are looking for businesses to collaborate with other stakeholders, such as universities and local leaders to produce a clear proposal for boosting the productivity of their sector. As part of the Industrial Strategy, the Government will consider how to increase energy productivity and will also set out during 2017 a long-term road map to minimise energy costs for businesses and industry.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-22T14:06:03.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690525/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690525/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690525/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Energy Intensive Industries: Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to help increase productivity for the (a) chemical, (b) steel, (c) aluminium and (d) other energy-intensive industries.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","64060"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690526","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>All of our published information on incidents attended by fire and rescue services (FRSs) can be found on this page - <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/fire-statistics-data-tables</a></p><p>Table 0602 on the above page includes information on fires, fatalities and casualties by source of ignition, grouped by broad categories. Fires relating to portable electric heaters are included within the ‘Space heating appliances’ category and electric blankets are included within the ‘Other electrical appliances’ category.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-27T11:19:11.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690526/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690526/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690526/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Domestic Appliances: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people aged 65 or over have been involved in fires caused by (a) portable electrical fires and (b) electric blankets in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","64130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690527","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Modern Slavery Act 2015 includes a ground breaking transparency in supply chains provision, which requires large commercial organisations operating in the UK to set out the steps they have taken to ensure there is no modern slavery in their business or supply chains. This includes large businesses in the textile industry.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-27T14:23:20.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690527/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690527/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690527/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-17","Textiles: Slavery","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to encourage transparency within supply chains for the textile industry to ensure that workers are not victims of modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","64128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690528","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The UK is one of the world’s top destinations for inward investment. As part of that, mergers can bring real benefits to consumers and the economy through higher growth, greater innovation and increased productivity.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-22T14:06:59.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690528/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690528/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690528/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Foreign Companies: Takeovers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of foreign company takeovers on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","64187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690529","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Government’s statutory powers to intervene in mergers are set out in the Enterprise Act 2002. My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State may intervene on specified public interest grounds, currently national security, financial stability and media plurality.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-22T14:07:52.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690529/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690529/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690529/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Foreign Companies: Takeovers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to prevent hostile foreign takeovers of UK firms.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","64188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690530","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Government believes it is in the best interests of business to tap into the widest talent pool and to have a diverse leadership which draws on a variety of backgrounds, skills and experiences. This is also true of Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs), and we have set out our expectations on this in the LEP assurance framework. Each LEP must have its own diversity statement, which sets out how boards can ensure diverse representation, reflective of their local business community. This should be used to guide local decisions on appointments to the LEP Board.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-22T10:31:38.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690530/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690530/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690530/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Local Enterprise Partnerships: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to increase female representation on the boards of local enterprise partnerships.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","64218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690531","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-23","<p>There are approximately 2 million customers benefitting from the Warm Home Discount rebate. Currently, participating energy suppliers administer the discount and cannot guarantee customers their rebate at exactly the same time, especially Broader Group customers who need to apply when supplier schemes open. This group make up approximately 40% of the scheme.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is working closely with Ofgem and delivery partners so that suppliers are able to deliver the maximum number of rebates as speedily as possible. For winter 2017/18, the Department for Work and Pensions will provide the bulk of Core Group customer details to energy suppliers in August 2017. The Digital Economy Bill currently going through Parliament will provide powers that can potentially further improve data matching.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-23T15:26:43.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690531/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690531/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690531/answer","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690531/answer/previousversion/36473","Biography information for Jesse Norman","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Warm Home Discount Scheme: Payments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will review payment dates for the Warm Home Discount Scheme to ensure that discounts are applied at the start of the winter season.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","64224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690532","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>This Government intends to secure the best possible outcome for the UK research base as we exit the European Union (EU). UK participants should continue to bid for competitive EU funds while we remain a member of the EU and we will work with the Commission to ensure payment when funds are awarded. The Treasury will underwrite the payment of such awards, even when specific projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Access to apply to the Horizon 2020 Marie Sklodowska-Curie Actions scheme and subsequent funding programmes after we leave the EU will be a matter for the negotiations that will follow the triggering of Article 50.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-27T11:26:52.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690532/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690532/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690532/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Research: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans the Government has to support the Ser Cymru II programme in Wales after the UK has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","64149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690533","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) was created on 14 July 2016. The Department of Energy and Climate Change (DECC) and the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) were merged to create this new department.</p><p>The Civil Service publishes pay information including mean and median pay broken down by various characteristics for each department including DECC and BIS. The latest pay data was published in October last year and can be found on the Office for National Statistics website.</p><p>BEIS will contribute to the next release but could only provide the data in the requested format for both departments at disproportionate cost.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-27T17:39:15.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690533/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690533/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690533/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690534","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Green Investment Bank (GIB) has invested £17.6m in the £47m Birmingham Bio Power project. Details of this project can be found on the Green Investment Bank website: <a href="http://www.greeninvestmentbank.com/news-and-insights/2013/gib-and-foresight-group-forge-consortium-to-construct-478m-renewable-energy-plant-in-birmingham/" target="_blank">http://www.greeninvestmentbank.com/news-and-insights/2013/gib-and-foresight-group-forge-consortium-to-construct-478m-renewable-energy-plant-in-birmingham/</a>.</p><p>In addition, some of GIB’s UK-wide investment platforms such as its indirect investment in LED lighting upgrades to Santander branches and NCP car parks are likely to have benefitted these areas. Further information on all of GIB’s investments can be found on its website: <a href="http://www.greeninvestmentbank.com/" target="_blank">www.greeninvestmentbank.com</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-02-22T11:29:51.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690534/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690534/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690534/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Green Investment Bank: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much (a) Birmingham and (b) the West Midlands has received in financial support through local projects funded by the Green Investment Bank since that bank was established.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","64204"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690535","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>While the UK remains in the EU, the Government will continue to engage constructively on new and existing EU legislation and regulation.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T12:35:01.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690535/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690535/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690535/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Energy: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans his Department has to implement the EU's Clean Energy for All Europeans package if it is adopted before Spring 2019.","false","Biography information for Matthew Pennycook","Greenwich and Woolwich","Matthew Pennycook","64205"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690536","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>Implementation of the recommendations will, as proposed by the independent review, be led by industry. Following the Stakeholder Launch of the Report on 2 February, Government will continue to work constructively with the sector to understand how and when they propose to implement the recommendations.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T12:34:00.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690536/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690536/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690536/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Consumer Advice, Protection, Standards and Enforcement for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Independent Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62374, what plans he has to report on the progress of industry implementation of the recommendations in his Department's Each Home Counts review, published in December 2016.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","64311"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690537","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Department has not made any assessment of the merits or feasibility of the re-use of decommissioned oil platforms for wind energy installations. The majority of infrastructure being decommissioned is very mature and has often operated well beyond its original design life. Nonetheless, companies must consider reuse as part of the decommissioning process.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T12:33:03.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690537/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690537/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690537/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Wind Power: Offshore Fixed Structures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of using decommissioned oil platforms for wind energy installations.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","64320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690538","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-23","<p>I have been in contact with the Scottish Government Cabinet Secretary for the Economy, Jobs and Fair Work to discuss this. Additionally, at official level there has been and will continue to be regular contact with Scottish Government officials throughout the process.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-02-23T15:21:48.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690538/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690538/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690538/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","EURATOM: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Scotland and Ministers of the Scottish Government on the effect on Scotland of the UK ceasing to be a member of Euratom.","false","Biography information for Ian Murray","Edinburgh South","Ian Murray","64290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690539","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-02-27","<p>The treatment of the workers in the Cammell Laird case as a result of the industrial action taken and any possible miscarriage of justice is not a matter for the Department of Business Energy and Industrial Strategy.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-02-27T17:33:51.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690539/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690539/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690539/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Cammell Laird: Industrial Disputes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will respond to the request for an apology for actions by the UK Government in relation to industrial action at Cammell Laird in 1984 made by the Committee on Petitions of the European Parliament in December 2014; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ruth Smeeth","Stoke-on-Trent North","Ruth Smeeth","64262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690540","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-03-02","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) has received correspondence from Xcite Energy Limited shareholders in recent months, and I was sorry to hear of the impact the company’s recent insolvency has had on them. BEIS and the Oil and Gas Authority continue to monitor the situation. The arrangements surrounding the sale process and the marketing of the assets is a matter for the court-appointed liquidators who, I understand, have been in contact with shareholders to explain the position.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-03-02T12:35:58.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690540/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690540/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690540/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-02-17","Xcite Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what recent representations he has received from Xcite Energy Limited shareholders.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","64263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690541","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-22","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade. In line with normal international practice, it would not be appropriate to routinely provide details of private diplomatic engagement with foreign governments.</p><p>Working groups are just one example of how we are engaging with our trading partners. Engagement ranges from informal contact through our network of Posts, discussions with embassies and High Commissions in London, to ministerial discussions and visits, and the Prime Minister’s 20 Trade Envoys.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-22T14:07:54.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690541/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690541/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690541/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-17","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 61491, which countries have expressed an interest in agreeing trade deals with the UK with whom a working group and dialogue on our future trading relationship have not been announced.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","64291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690542","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-27","<p>At present, the Department for International Trade (DIT) operates within shared buildings, in which it does not represent the majority tenant. Therefore, the responsibility for issuing passes does not fall directly to DIT but to the local Departmental Security teams who are responsible for the building.</p><p>Passes are issued to contractors, secondees, public sector workers (e.g. from Non-Departmental Public Bodies) or Crown Servants, such as Police or Military forces, as well as to Civil Servants where it is necessary and appropriate to do so. This enables teams to work flexibly and effectively to best support business needs. Use of all security passes is underpinned by a strong physical security focus, access control procedures and technologies, clear processes and assurance mechanisms that enable an integrated workforce to operate in a secure manner.</p><p>DIT does not separate the information between these defined categories. Therefore, we do not record them in this way. Strict processes are followed before a pass is authorised and ultimately revoked.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-27T14:49:15.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690542/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690542/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690542/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-17","Department for International Trade: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 8 February 2017 to Question 62539, how many security passes are issued on behalf of his Department by the Departmental Security teams in the buildings in which they are based to people who are not employees of his Department.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","64317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690543","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-22","<p>The number of officials working on trade policy has increased from 45 before the referendum to 185. Under the Autumn Statement, the Trade Policy Group has funding to increase resourcing further in 2017-18. In line with the approach of many of our counterparts, trade policy officials work flexibly on a range of issues, including cross-cutting policy work, so we do not allocate a fixed number of staff to specific working groups with particular countries.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-22T14:06:06.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690543/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690543/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690543/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-17","Department for International Trade: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, pursuant to the Answer of 27 January 2017 to Question 60711, how many UK-based full-time equivalent staff of his Department are in the working group on  the UK's future trading relationship with (a) Australia, (b) China, (c) India, (d) New Zealand, (e) Norway, (f) South Korea and (g) the Gulf Cooperation Council.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","64292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690544","Department for International Trade","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Office for National Statistics (ONS) publishes much of this information each year, broken down by Civil Service organization, as part of their annual release of Civil Service Statistics. The latest data set from 2016 can be found on the ONS website: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/publicsectorpersonnel/bulletins/civilservicestatistics/2016</a>.</p><p>As the Department for International Trade (DIT) is newly formed, we have not had the opportunity to contribute to the most recent ONS publication. DIT’s statistics will be included in the next release, due for publication in March 2017.</p><p>DIT does not hold information on the breakdowns of ethnicity and disability pay gaps.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2017-02-24T11:31:39.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690544/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690544/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690544/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-02-17","Department for International Trade: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64171"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690545","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-27","<p>The Civil Service is committed to being a place where everyone can thrive, regardless of background- with the aim of becoming the most inclusive employer in the UK.<br> <br>Whilst it is encouraging to see a positive trajectory in terms of diversity representation in the Civil Service, we recognise that there is more to do. That is why in March 2016 the Government published its refreshed Talent Action Plan for the Civil Service, identifying actions to support our staff, increase diversity in the Civil Service and deliver the best possible public services.<br><br>The Department for Exiting the European Union does not hold this information, as it did not exist in the 2015-16 financial year. Civil Service has been publishing mean and median gender pay gaps for each department since 2008 as part of the annual release of Civil Service Statistics by the Office for National Statistics. The latest gender pay gap data (published in October last year) can be found on the Office for National Statistics website.<strong><br></strong></p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2017-02-27T15:55:34.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690545/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690545/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690545/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-17","Department for Exiting the European Union: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the (a) mean and (b) median pay was for staff in his Department who were (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) white, (iv) from an ethnic minority background, (v) disabled and (vi) non-disabled in the most recent year for which information is available, broken down by (A) full-time and (B) part-time workers.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","64165"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690546","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>The average time taken to process electronic customs declarations is defined in the contract with the service supplier. This states that 95% should be processed in 5 seconds and 99.9% in 20 seconds. These targets have been achieved for each of the last three years.</p><p> </p><p>Non-electronic customs declarations are input by HM Revenue and Customs to the electronic system. Once these customs declarations are on the electronic system, the above clearance times are achieved.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-22T13:58:08.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690546/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690546/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690546/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-17","Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 8.44 of the White Paper, entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm9417, published in February 2017, what the average time taken was for customs declarations submitted (a) electronically and (b) non-electronically in the UK to be cleared in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","64251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690547","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>In 2014, 66,585,140 declarations were submitted, of which 99% were submitted electronically.</p><p> </p><p>In 2015, 77,493,171 declarations were submitted, of which 99% were submitted electronically.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016, 55,234,357 declarations were submitted, of which 99% were submitted electronically.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-22T14:03:45.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690547/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690547/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690547/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-17","Customs","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 8.44 of the White Paper, entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm9417, published in February 2017, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of customs declarations in the UK were submitted electronically in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","64252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690548","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-02-22","<p>As set out in the recent White Paper (The United Kingdom’s exit from and new partnership with the European Union), the Government will discuss with the EU and Member States our future status and arrangements with regard to EU agencies. It would not be appropriate to prejudge the outcome of the negotiations.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-02-22T12:08:44.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690548/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690548/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/690548/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-02-17","EU Institutions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to paragraph 8.42 of the White Paper entitled The United Kingdom's exit from and new partnership with the European Union, Cm 9417, published in February 2017, if he will list all the EU agencies to be included in discussions with the EU and Member States on the UK's future status and arrangements with regard to those agencies.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","64155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687891","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>A reply was sent on 10 February. This answer addresses all three Parliamentary questions relating to the letter sent by the right hon. Member for Hitchin and Harpenden on 23 January 2017.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby","63795 ; 63797","2017-02-20T13:18:21.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687891/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687891/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Head of the Civil Service plans to reply to the letter and email he received from the right hon. Member for Hitchin and Harpenden on 23 January 2017 on flaws in HM Treasury's analysis of the impact of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Lilley","Hitchin and Harpenden","Mr Peter Lilley","63796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687892","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","63812 ; 63814","2017-02-24T15:09:19.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687892/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687892/answer","PQ63812 & 63814 & 63816 v.02.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Temporary Contract","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687892/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Social Services: Hemsworth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in Hemsworth constituency (a) work in social care and (b) work in social care and are paid less that the living wage.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687893","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p>Zero hours contracts only account for 2.9% of all people in work. For many people they offer the right kind of flexibility, with independent research showing that nearly two-thirds of people on such contracts are satisfied with their job.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","63813","2017-02-24T15:09:07.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687893/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687893/answer","PQ 63811& 63813 v.02.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Zero Hour Contracts","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687893/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Zero Hours Contracts: Hemsworth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people in each year from 2010 have been employed on zero-hour contracts in Hemsworth constituency.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63811"
