"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687899","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Government has 69 freehold holdings in Glasgow Central, of which 68 are land holdings held by the Department for Transport.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-22T10:14:18.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687899/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687899/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Government: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many properties and assets the Government fully owns in Glasgow Central constituency.","false","Biography information for Alison Thewliss","Glasgow Central","Alison Thewliss","63839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687900","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>As at the 31<sup>st</sup> December 2016, the number of Building Access (security) passes issued by the Cabinet Office to people (a) not directly employed by and (b) who are not civil servants and who work or regularly visit the Cabinet Office was 39. In addition 345 passes have been issued to staff of external contractors who are employed full time working for the Cabinet Office.</p><p>The numbers of such passes will fluctuate significantly over the course of a year.</p><p>Such passes are issued to contractors, secondees, other public sector workers or Crown Servants (such as the police or military forces) as well as to civil servants where it is necessary and appropriate to do so. The business needs for determining the issuing of such passes will vary. They are always considered on a case by case basis and dependent upon a range of factors, such as the regularity/purpose/frequency of the person attending and any specific security issues and against a backdrop of ensuring that both business efficiency and the security of all our assets is maintained at all times.</p><p>All such passes are cancelled immediately when they are no longer required. Their use and provision is underpinned by a strong physical security focus, access control procedures and technologies, clear processes and assurance mechanisms that enable an integrated workforce to operate in a secure manner.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-24T12:03:46.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687900/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687900/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Cabinet Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62529, what the number of security passes issued by his Department to people not employed by his Department is; what business needs suffice for such a security pass to be granted; and what the number of passes issued to people who work for private companies which have currently or previously been awarded government contracts or which are bidding for such contracts is.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687901","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>All departments are equipping themselves with the resources they need to get the best deal for the UK. We are not in a position to give a final total for particular groups of staff as recruitment is ongoing and we will not be giving a running commentary on negotiations.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-02-20T10:39:21.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687901/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687901/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687901/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Government Departments: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of how many staff and negotiators government departments will need to recruit for the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Richard Arkless","Dumfries and Galloway","Richard  Arkless","63877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687902","Cabinet Office","false","2017-03-06","<p>The PwC staff are seconded to HM Treasury and the Crown Commercial Service.</p><p> </p><p>The individual seconded to HM Treasury is undertaking a role at pay band 1 of the Senior Civil Service, in the Finance Insight Team of the Public Spending Group. The secondment is from 04 October 2016 until 29 September 2017.</p><p> </p><p>The individual seconded to the Crown Commercial Service is undertaking a role at Civil Service Grade 6 in the Strategic Programmes Directorate. The secondment is from 16 January 2017 until 16 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>These secondments are part of a centrally-managed talent programme in the Cabinet Office.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2017-03-06T11:19:30.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687902/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687902/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Government Departments: Secondment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62723, on government secondments, (a) what positions the staff from PWC were seconded to, (b) what the purpose of those secondments were, (c) what the equivalent payscales were of the positions to which those staff were seconded and (d) how long those secondments lasted.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687903","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-22","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-02-22T10:10:25.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687903/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687903/answer","UKSA response to 63903.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - UK Population","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687903/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Population","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the February 2017 release of the Overview of the UK Population series has been cancelled; what plans the Office of National Statistics has to publish such releases in the future; and what plans there are to continue that series in future.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63903"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687904","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Government, announced savings and benefits totalling £3.3 billion in 2015/16 on 3<sup>rd</sup> February 2017, building on total savings of £52billion during the last parliament. A detailed breakdown of these savings and benefits was published alongside a technical note, including the individual methodologies from each of the savings workstreams featured in this announcement. Independent analysis of the savings and benefits by the Government Internal Audit Agency is provided in the Savings Validation Report, also published at the same time as the announcement.</p><p>These savings and benefits were realised in government Departments, with support, expertise and assurance from Cabinet Office Functions; Commercial, Property, Digital, and Fraud, Error, Debt and Grants.</p><p>This announcement is part of the Government’s continued drive to embed greater efficiency in the way the government does business. The announcement includes £1.2billion of operational savings from commercial activities and optimising the government’s property portfolio.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","63950","2017-02-24T11:38:21.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687904/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687904/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Cabinet Office: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, whether his Department will publish a social economic distributional analysis of the cost savings from the Cabinet Office in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687905","Cabinet Office","false","2017-02-24","<p>The Government, announced savings and benefits totalling £3.3 billion in 2015/16 on 3<sup>rd</sup> February 2017, building on total savings of £52billion during the last parliament. A detailed breakdown of these savings and benefits was published alongside a technical note, including the individual methodologies from each of the savings workstreams featured in this announcement. Independent analysis of the savings and benefits by the Government Internal Audit Agency is provided in the Savings Validation Report, also published at the same time as the announcement.</p><p>These savings and benefits were realised in government Departments, with support, expertise and assurance from Cabinet Office Functions; Commercial, Property, Digital, and Fraud, Error, Debt and Grants.</p><p>This announcement is part of the Government’s continued drive to embed greater efficiency in the way the government does business. The announcement includes £1.2billion of operational savings from commercial activities and optimising the government’s property portfolio.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","63949","2017-02-24T11:38:21.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687905/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687905/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-02-09","Cabinet Office: Cost Effectiveness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, whether his Department will publish a gender impact assessment of the cost savings from the Cabinet Office in the last financial year.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687906","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63952 ; 63953 ; 63958 ; 63959 ; 63962","2017-02-22T10:39:13.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687906/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687906/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Government: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, what the criteria is for determining the level of economic or social return when considering the sales of government assets.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687907","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63951 ; 63953 ; 63958 ; 63959 ; 63962","2017-02-22T10:39:13.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687907/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687907/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Public Sector: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, how his Department defines value for money in relation to the policy to sell public assets; and whether he will place a copy of the evidence base for that definition in the Library.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63952"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687908","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63951 ; 63952 ; 63958 ; 63959 ; 63962","2017-02-22T10:39:13.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687908/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687908/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Government: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, what criteria his Department is using to determine whether there is a policy reason to continue to own government assets.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63953"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687909","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63951 ; 63952 ; 63953 ; 63959 ; 63962","2017-02-22T10:39:13.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687909/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687909/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Public Sector: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, who in his Department is responsible for the sale process of public assets.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63958"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687910","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63951 ; 63952 ; 63953 ; 63958 ; 63962","2017-02-22T10:39:13.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687910/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687910/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Public Sector: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, what methodology his Department will use to assess market conditions as part of the sale process of public assets.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63959"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687911","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>The framework for assessing the value for money of the sale of part of the student loan book has been set by HM Treasury, in accordance with Green Book principles. The final assessment will be overseen by the Accounting Officer of the Department for Education.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-23T16:25:51.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687911/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687911/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-09","Public Sector: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, who will be overseeing the final value for money assessment in accordance with her Department's Green Book framework during the sale process of public assets.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687912","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>The Government will guarantee projects funded by European Structural and Investment Funds where contracts have been signed prior to the UK leaving the EU. Such assurances apply even when these projects continue beyond the UK’s departure from the EU. Funding for these projects will be honoured by the Government provided they are good value for money and are in line with domestic strategic priorities.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-22T10:45:13.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687912/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687912/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will ensure that the value of EU structural funds is met by the  Government after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687913","Department for Education","false","2017-02-23","<p>The sale of the rights to the remaining future repayments on the loans in scope of the sale of part of the student loan book, as set out in a Written Statement on 6 February, would be structured as a securitisation. In this structure, the loans are sold to a new independent English-domiciled company (“the Issuer”) which issues the notes to investors and makes payments of interest and principal on them.</p><p>This structure will enable the Government to maximise value from the sale for the taxpayer by creating separate tranches of securities attractive to a range of potential investors.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-02-23T16:25:14.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687913/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687913/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-02-09","Students: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, how the Government plans to securitise the remaining future repayments on student loans as a part of their planned sale process.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63961"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687914","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-22","<p>HM Treasury’s “Green Book” outlines the framework that is used to assess the value for money of public spending decisions, including asset sales. Supplementary guidance is provided in “Value for money and the valuation of public sector assets”.</p><p> </p><p>The Department to whom an asset belongs is responsible for the sale process of that asset. The Economic Secretary to the Treasury is the minister responsible for the financial sector assets which the Treasury owns (Royal Bank of Scotland, Lloyds and UK Asset Resolution).</p><p> </p><p>Whether there is a policy reason for the government to continue to hold an asset is assessed on a case-by-case basis. With regards to student loans, the policy objective of issuing a loan is to allow access to higher education. This purpose is achieved once the loan is made.</p><p> </p><p>The government takes expert advice on market conditions ahead of any significant asset sale.</p><p> </p><p>The government will inform the House by way of a statement when the sale of a significant public asset is completed.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","63951 ; 63952 ; 63953 ; 63958 ; 63959","2017-02-22T10:39:13.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687914/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687914/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Public Sector: Assets","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Written Statement of 6 February 2017, HCWS458, how the Government will inform the House when a sale of a public asset is completed.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63962"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687915","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>Overall levels of tax credit error and fraud and the evidential basis for those results are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/search?q=tax+credit+error+and+fraud+statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/search?q=tax+credit+error+and+fraud+statistics</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom has one of the lowest tax gaps in the world. The most recent ‘Measuring tax gaps’ publication indicates that the estimated tax gaps attributable to avoidance behaviour for the last three years for which data is available were as follows:</p><p> </p><p>2014-15 - £2.2 billion</p><p>2013-14 - £2.4 billion</p><p>2012-13 - £2.2 billion</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The publication is available to view in full at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/measuring-tax-gaps</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested on the estimated value of benefit fraud is available via the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fraud-and-error-in-the-benefit-system" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/fraud-and-error-in-the-benefit-system</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:55:53.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687915/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687915/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the value is of (a) fraudulent tax credit claims, (b) benefit fraud and (c) tax avoidance in each of the last three years; and what the evidential basis is for those estimates.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63945"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687916","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) carries out a range of activities in relation to tax credits, tax avoidance and the enforcement of the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not hold information in the format requested, and so this could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Work and Pensions is responsible for benefit fraud prosecutions.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:57:40.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687916/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687916/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many cases (a) HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and (b) other bodies working on behalf of HMRC have pursued on (i) fraudulent tax credit claims, (ii) benefit fraud, (iii) tax avoidance and (iv) breaches of minimum wage legislation in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63946"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687917","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) carries out a range of activities in these areas. The costs specifically of tackling fraudulent tax credit claims, tax avoidance and breaches of the National Minimum Wage are not held in that format and this information could only be gathered at disproportionate cost. HMRC does not have an enforcement role in respect of benefit fraud.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:05:05.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687917/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687917/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much (a) HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) and (b) other bodies working on behalf of HMRC have spent from the public purse on tackling (i) fraudulent tax credit claims, (ii) benefit fraud, (iii) tax avoidance and (iv) breaches of minimum wage legislation in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687918","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Latest statistics on inheritance tax exemptions and reliefs claimed by estates in 2013-14 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs</a></p><p> </p><p>This publication contains information on how many estates claimed inheritance tax relief on transfers to charities on death (PQ02515), transfers to surviving spouses on death (PQ02519), conditional exemptions for heritage property (PQ02521), business property including unlisted shares (PQ02525) and agricultural property (PQ02526).</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014-15 is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63826 ; 63827 ; 63968 ; 63969","2017-02-20T15:35:25.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687918/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687918/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received inheritance tax relief for estates exempt of transfers to charities on death in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687919","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>Only companies are able to claim cross field allowance for petroleum revenue tax relief. Fewer than ten companies claimed the relief in each of 2013-14 and 2014-15.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:36:48.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687919/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687919/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Petroleum Revenue Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) people and (b) businesses received the cross field allowance for petroleum revenue tax relief in (i) 2013-14 and (ii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687920","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>The requested information is not available. [HM Revenue and Customs’ data covers all error and fraud activity. It cannot be broken down to subsequently show those cases which were found to contain error and those containing fraud.]</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:04:11.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687920/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687920/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Fraud: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the correlation is between the amount HM Revenue and Customs has spent and recouped on tackling fraudulent (a) tax credit and (b) benefit claims.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","63947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687921","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-24","<p>Information on the number of people and businesses that received acquisition relief in 2013-14 and 2014-15 cannot be provided due to the small numbers involved. Providing this information would risk breaching HM Revenue and Customs’ taxpayer confidentiality principles.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2017-02-24T12:34:49.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687921/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687921/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Stamp Duty Land Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many (a) people and (b) businesses received the acquisition relief from stamp duty land tax in (i) 2013-14 and (ii) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687922","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Latest statistics on inheritance tax exemptions and reliefs claimed by estates in 2013-14 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs</a></p><p> </p><p>This publication contains information on how many estates claimed inheritance tax relief on transfers to charities on death (PQ02515), transfers to surviving spouses on death (PQ02519), conditional exemptions for heritage property (PQ02521), business property including unlisted shares (PQ02525) and agricultural property (PQ02526).</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014-15 is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63826 ; 63827 ; 63965 ; 63969","2017-02-20T15:35:25.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687922/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687922/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received inheritance tax exemption of transfers on death to surviving spouses in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687923","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Latest statistics on inheritance tax exemptions and reliefs claimed by estates in 2013-14 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs</a></p><p> </p><p>This publication contains information on how many estates claimed inheritance tax relief on transfers to charities on death (PQ02515), transfers to surviving spouses on death (PQ02519), conditional exemptions for heritage property (PQ02521), business property including unlisted shares (PQ02525) and agricultural property (PQ02526).</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014-15 is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63826 ; 63827 ; 63965 ; 63968","2017-02-20T15:35:25.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687923/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687923/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received inheritance tax relief for estates left on death with conditional exemption for heritage property in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63969"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687924","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Each government department will take responsibility for the allocation of money to projects in line with the stated criteria and the wider rules on public spending. These conditions will be applied in such a way that the current pipeline of committed projects is not disrupted.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2017-02-20T12:33:35.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687924/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687924/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what mechanism has been put in place to assess whether the Government will guarantee funding for specific ESF and ERDF projects signed after the Autumn Statement; how such projects will be assessed against the two criteria of value for money and alignment with domestic priorities; and whether such assessments will be undertaken before or after agreements have been signed.","false","Biography information for Mr Clive Betts","Sheffield South East","Mr Clive Betts","63865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687925","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Treasury ministers and officials meet regularly with the Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) to discuss relevant regulatory issues. As was the case with previous administrations, it is not the Treasury's practice to provide details of all such discussions.</p><p> </p><p>The government is committed to increasing competition in banking and welcomes the CMA’s final report on its retail banking market investigation as an important step towards the goal of a highly competitive banking system. It is the CMA’s role to review the market, assess how effectively competition is working and, where appropriate, propose remedies to address any issues. That is why we set up the CMA as a single, stronger and independent competition regulator.</p><p> </p><p>The CMA proposed a series of remedies in its final report to improve overdraft transparency, including requiring banks to set a monthly maximum charge for unarranged overdraft charges.</p><p> </p><p>The government welcomed the Financial Conduct Authority’s (FCA) response to the CMA’s investigation. In its response, the FCA committed to look in more detail at overdrafts from both a consumer and competition perspective, as part of its broader review of the high-cost credit market.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2017-02-20T12:07:53.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687925/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687925/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Bank Services: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the Markets and Competition Authority on the introduction of a cap on overdraft charges for personal current accounts; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","63848"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687926","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>The number of people or businesses receiving the annual exempt amount against capital gains tax is not available, nor are the number of people or businesses receiving capital gains tax relief on investments in enterprise investment schemes. I refer the honourable lady to the answer given to a previous question at <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-01-23/61243/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-01-23/61243</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of people receiving capital gains tax relief for entrepreneurs' qualifying business disposals in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15 is available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/numbers-of-claimants-of-entrepreneurs-relief-and-amounts-of-gain-by-year" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/numbers-of-claimants-of-entrepreneurs-relief-and-amounts-of-gain-by-year</a></p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63828 ; 63829","2017-02-20T15:31:45.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687926/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687926/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Entrepreneurs' Relief","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received capital gains tax relief for entrepreneurs' qualifying business disposals in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687927","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-20","<p>Latest statistics on inheritance tax exemptions and reliefs claimed by estates in 2013-14 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/inheritance-tax-statistics-table-122-exemptions-and-reliefs</a></p><p> </p><p>This publication contains information on how many estates claimed inheritance tax relief on transfers to charities on death (PQ02515), transfers to surviving spouses on death (PQ02519), conditional exemptions for heritage property (PQ02521), business property including unlisted shares (PQ02525) and agricultural property (PQ02526).</p><p> </p><p>Data for 2014-15 is not currently available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","63827 ; 63965 ; 63968 ; 63969","2017-02-20T15:35:25.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687927/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/687927/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-02-09","Inheritance Tax","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received inheritance tax relief for business relief including unlisted shares in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Rebecca Long Bailey","Salford and Eccles","Rebecca Long Bailey","63826"
