"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688015","Department of Health","false","2017-02-20","<p>Healthcare in Immigration Removal Centres (IRCs) is commissioned by NHS England. Testing for infectious diseases among new entrants to IRCs, including Yarl’s Wood, is guided by advice from Public Health England and, where applicable, National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance.</p><p> </p><p>New entrants to all IRCs have a symptom-based questionnaire at first reception screening where healthcare staff ascertain whether patients have either signs or symptoms of tuberculosis (TB) or past history of infection or recent contact with someone with TB.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2014, IRCs are advised to offer testing for HIV, hepatitis B and hepatitis C to new entrants as part of an ‘opt-out programme’ for blood-borne virus testing promoted by Public Health England, NHS England and the Home Office through the National Partnership Agreement.</p><p> </p><p>Testing for malaria is usually done following presentation of symptoms consistent with malaria in someone with a history of travel from endemic countries and is not done routinely on asymptomatic patients.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-20T11:56:09.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688015/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688015/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688015/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-02-09","Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether women in Yarl's Wood Immigration Removal Centre are tested for TB, HIV and malaria on arrival from (a) West Africa, (b) East Africa, (c) South Africa and (d) South-East Asia.","false","Biography information for Kate Osamor","Edmonton","Kate Osamor","63781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688016","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The first Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner was appointed by Government on a three year fixed term contract, which ends on 26 November 2017</p><p> </p><p>Any future appointment process, later this year, will comply with the New Public Appointments Governance Code which was published on 16 December 2016.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-20T14:43:06.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688016/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688016/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688016/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when she plans to commence the appointment process for the second Independent Anti-Slavery Commissioner.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","63858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688017","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The threat posed by frauds enabled by social engineering, such as in CEO fraud, is one this Government takes very seriously. Through the Joint Fraud Taskforce, a truly innovative collaboration between the financial sector, law enforcement and Government, we are driving system-wide improvements to remove vulnerabilities which fraudster exploit to commit this type of crime. The Taskforce is investing in a nationwide fraud prevention campaign ‘Take 5’, funded by the financial sector and Government, so that individuals know how to act when faced by a fraudster to avoid being scammed. The Taskforce is also developing a funds repatriation scheme, so that stolen money can be tracked across the payment network, frozen, then repatriated back to the victim of the crime also stopping the money from getting into the hands of the criminal.</p><p>The Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) has the objective of protecting and enhancing the integrity of the UK financial system. The FCA’s rules require that firms must maintain effective systems and controls to prevent the risk that they might be exploited by criminals. These systems and controls should enable the firm to identify, assess, monitor and manage money laundering risk. A firm’s systems and controls must be comprehensive and proportionate to the nature, scale and complexity of its activities. Where a firm’s systems and controls are not adequate, the FCA can and does take enforcement action. On 31 January, the FCA fined Deutsche Bank £163,076,224 for failing to maintain an adequate anti-money laundering (AML) control framework during the period between 1 January 2012 and 31 December 2015. This is the largest financial penalty for AML controls failings ever imposed by the FCA.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-02-20T15:55:01.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688017/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688017/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688017/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to (a) protect businesses subject to CEO fraud and (b) hold accountable banks which have not followed money-laundering check procedures in opening accounts.","false","Biography information for Charlotte Leslie","Bristol North West","Charlotte Leslie","63881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688018","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>Cyber Specials can be either Special Constables or volunteers.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the latest information provided by police forces, there are at least 40 Cyber Specials in police forces across England and Wales. At least 21 have been recruited since January 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The NCA currently have 22 Specials whose area of expertise is cyber crime. 19 of those were recruited since January 2015.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","63928","2017-02-23T12:54:25.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688018/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688018/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688018/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many cyber specials there are in police forces in England Wales; and how many of those officers have been recruited since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688019","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The table below shows the number of passports lost by Her Majesty’s Passport Office (HM Passport Office) delivery partner DX from January 2011 until September 2016. The data for the period from September 2016 onwards is currently being verified and therefore is unavailable.</p><p> </p><p>HM Passport Office records and cancels any passport lost through delivery, and the customer is issued with a new passport at no extra cost.</p><p> </p><p>This is Management Information and subject to change. These statistics have been taken from a live operational database. As such, the numbers may change as information on that system is updated.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Losses</p></td><td><p>Passports printed</p></td><td><p>% Passport losses against passports printed</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>173</p></td><td><p>4,971,659</p></td><td><p>0.003</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>214</p></td><td><p>5,315,465</p></td><td><p>0.004</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>186</p></td><td><p>5,609,530</p></td><td><p>0.003</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>234</p></td><td><p>6,228,867</p></td><td><p>0.004</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>298</p></td><td><p>6,762,898</p></td><td><p>0.004</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016 Jan – Sept 16</p></td><td><p>186</p></td><td><p>5,898,335</p></td><td><p>0.003</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-23T12:51:47.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688019/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688019/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688019/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passports have been lost in the post in each of the last six years.","false","Biography information for Tim Farron","Westmorland and Lonsdale","Tim Farron","63861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688020","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>Providers of asylum accommodation are contractually obliged to ensure that they understand any particular characteristics and special needs of those in their care, and provide adequate and appropriate signposting to health services and support systems. All accommodation needs to be safe, habitable and fit for purpose and monitoring mechanisms are in place to ensure property standards are met and maintained.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-20T15:08:50.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688020/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688020/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688020/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Asylum: Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that premises used by asylum accommodation providers as temporary accommodation are fit to house vulnerable people.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","63852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688021","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>Asylum seekers are usually moved from Initial Accommodation to Dispersed Accommodation before their asylum claim is decided. When a supported asylum seeker is granted leave they are given 28 days accommodation and support to allow them to access mainstream benefits and the labour market and secure accommodation. The Home Office works closely with Department of Work and Pensions (DWP) to ensure that claims for mainstream benefits are processed during the 28 day grace period.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-20T15:12:11.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688021/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688021/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688021/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that people granted asylum in the UK in initial accommodation are properly supported for the duration of their stay.","false","Biography information for Mrs Anne Main","St Albans","Mrs Anne Main","63853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688022","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The Home Office collects data from the National Fraud Intelligence Bureau (NFIB) on the number of recorded fraud offences in England and Wales, including offences recorded by Action Fraud. These data, which are published by the ONS, are available on their website at: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice#datasets" target="_blank">https://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/crimeandjustice#datasets</a> (see ‘Crime in England and Wales: Appendix tables’ – Table A4).</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office also collects data on the number of dissemination packages that were transferred to the police. Dissemination packages contain cases of reported fraud that NFIB have assessed as having sufficient grounds to allocate it to a police force for investigation. One dissemination package could contain multiple fraud offences. Disseminations data are published by the Home Office and are available on Gov.uk at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/crime-outcomes-in-england-and-wales-2015-to-2016</a> (see ‘Crime Outcomes in England and Wales: year ending March 2016 – data tables’ – Table B1).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-20T14:49:14.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688022/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688022/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688022/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many fraud offences were recorded by Action Fraud in each year since 2013; and how many of those offences were then passed onto the police.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63933"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688023","Home Office","false","2017-02-21","<p>As of January 2017, there were approximately 75 Full Time Employee call handling staff.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2017-02-21T10:47:56.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688023/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688023/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688023/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Action Fraud: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many call-handling staff are employed by Action Fraud.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63934"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688024","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The direct funding provided by the Home Office for the Digital Media Investigators course ensured that a national cadre was successfully established by March 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Throughout 2016/17 the College of Policing has continued to deliver Digital Media Investigator training, addressing demand from police forces who require training. This is planned to continue into 2017-2018.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-20T15:53:59.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688024/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688024/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688024/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Police: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if her Department will make an assessment of the effect of its decision to stop direct funding for the digital media investigators course on the level of take-up of that course.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63935"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688025","Home Office","false","2017-02-27","<p>The allocation of 2017-18 money through the Police Transformation Fund is not yet complete and there will be further opportunities for forces to bid for money. The Government welcomes proposals that transform the police response to the changing nature of crime, including cyber crime, in line with the National Policing Vision 2025. On 1 November 2016 the Government published the National Cyber Security Strategy, underpinned by transformative investment of £1.9 billion over the next 5 years, including to reduce the impact of cyber crime on the UK and its interests.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-27T10:30:40.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688025/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688025/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688025/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much of the Police Transformation Fund for 2017-18 has been allocated to bids related to improving police forces' capacity to deal with cybercrime.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63936"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688026","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>The College of Policing was established in 2012 as the professional body for everyone who works for the police service in England and Wales. The College collects information on course attendance and has provided the data for this response. The number of officers and police staff who have undertaken each training course since 2013 is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Course</p></td><td><p>Number of officers and staff completing the course since 2013</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(a) Digital Communications, Social Media, Cybercrime and Policing</p></td><td><p>79,719</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) Cybercrime and digital policing - an introduction</p></td><td><p>116,096</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) Cybercrime and digital policing - First responder Training</p></td><td><p>105,747</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(d) Cybercrime and digital policing – Investigation</p></td><td><p>88,178</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(e) Communications Data in Investigations</p></td><td><p>7,713</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(f) Introduction to Communications Data and Cybercrime</p></td><td><p>11,825</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(g) Communications Data - Introduction to the Internet</p></td><td><p>9,428</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(h) Communications Data and Cybercrime - Introduction to Law and Procedure e-learning packages.</p></td><td><p>5,970</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-23T12:57:43.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688026/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688026/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688026/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Police: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many officers have completed the College of Policing (a) Digital Communications, Social Media, Cybercrime and Policing, (b) Cybercrime and digital policing - an introduction, (c) Cybercrime and digital policing - First responder Training, (d) Cybercrime and digital policing - Investigation, (e) Communications Data in Investigations, (f) Introduction to Communications Data and Cybercrime, (g) Communications Data - Introduction to the Internet and (h) Communications Data and Cybercrime - Introduction to Law and Procedure e-learning packages.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688027","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>The issuing of all passes is carried out in accordance with the department’s security policy. The information requested is not required as part of the process for issuing passes.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-20T14:44:38.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688027/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688027/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688027/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Home Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62601, on security at her Department, how many security passes have been issued to people who work for private companies who have (a) currently or previously been awarded government contracts and (b) previously or are currently bidding for government contracts.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63902"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688028","Home Office","false","2017-02-23","<p>Cyber Specials can be either Special Constables or volunteers.</p><p> </p><p>Based on the latest information provided by police forces, there are at least 40 Cyber Specials in police forces across England and Wales. At least 21 have been recruited since January 2015.</p><p> </p><p>The NCA currently have 22 Specials whose area of expertise is cyber crime. 19 of those were recruited since January 2015.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","63910","2017-02-23T12:54:25.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688028/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688028/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688028/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many National Crime Agency Special Officers there are whose area of expertise is cybercrime; and how many such officers were recruited since January 2015.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","63928"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688029","Home Office","false","2017-02-20","<p>I am sorry but this information is not available and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-02-20T14:43:53.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688029/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688029/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/688029/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-02-09","Home Office: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2017 to Question 62601, on Home Office Security, how many passes for the groups provided in that Answer were have been issued.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","63904"
